	<text>
		<body>
			<p><pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB1640_01.jpg"/> The person in question has given us the following information: <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-339" type="subject">Jewish laws</term> concerned me only in as much as my
				application was accepted only by the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1132" type="subject"
					>University</term> of <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3046526/pecs.html">Pécs</placeName>, and even there I needed the
				support of someone to get in. At the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1132" type="subject"
					>university</term>, I witnessed some harassment, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-345" type="subject"
					>beatings</term> and things like that. <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-329" type="subject"
					>Antisemitism</term> was intense at that time and in some cases I also received some beatings. Having done some <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-899" type="subject">lawyer’s practice</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3047967/mohacs.html">Mohács</placeName> and <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3046526/pecs.html">Pécs</placeName> I came to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3054643/budapest.html">Pest</placeName> and found a job. Later, however, I obtained new training and
				worked for the weaving <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-560">factory</term> Star. I had no
				problems here since I worked as a physical labourer. The <date when="1943-03-15">15th of March, 1943</date>, I left the <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-560">factory</term> and was drafted for <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-560" type="subject">labour service</term> in <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3047967/mohacs.html">Mohács</placeName>. Later, I was resent to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3054643/budapest.html">Pest</placeName> to work in the package selection department of the post
				office No. 70., and later I worked as a draftsman for the boss. Here I had a good life till I was sent into <placeName
					ref="#ehri_et_transylvania">Transylvania</placeName>. In <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/679550/dej.html">Dés</placeName>,
				in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/672026/ocna-dejului.html">Désakna</placeName> we had a malevolent <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">commander</term>, a criminal, 2nd Lieutenant <persName
					ref="#ehri_et_feher_ferenc">Ferenc Fehér</persName>, who came from <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3042771/vizvar.html"
					>Vízvár</placeName> in Somogy. There was also <persName ref="#ehri_et_kokonyei_ferenc">Ferenc Kökönyei</persName> who <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-655" type="subject">stole</term> my watch and wore it. The <date
					when="1944-02-19">19th of February, 1944</date>, at 10 pm <persName ref="#ehri_et_steckel_bela">Béla Steckel</persName>, who was
				on night patrol, took me and 11 of my companions to the headquarters from the Jewish Casino although I had a regular permission for a
				leave. Here I had to stand 40 minutes and he slapped me and broke my eardrum. <pb n="2" facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB1640_02.jpg"/> I made a
				great fuss about it, I went to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1076" type="subject">army corps
					headquarters</term> but in the meanwhile <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-633" type="subject">Germans
					entered</term> the country and I had to withdraw the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-200"
					type="subject">denunciation</term>. First, we <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject"
					>worked</term> on railway construction for the railway co., later we lay military cables in the ground between <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/669258/radna.html">Óradna</placeName> and <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/668090/comuna-sant.html">Újradna</placeName>. We had to walk 28 kilometres a day back and forth to
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">workplace</term>. We <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term> only during the time that remained. Our
				correspondence (both incoming and outgoing) was destroyed by the captain of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1076" type="subject">troop</term>, so we gathered torn pieces of <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-843">letters</term> from the toilet. I had another incident
				with <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">Cadet Sergeant</term>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_fejs_karoly">Károly Fejs</persName> (from <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3044760/szekszard.html"
					>Szekszárd</placeName>) who <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">beat me</term> and
				kicked my bottom because I went to get hold of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject"
					>food</term>. During the withdrawal from <placeName ref="#ehri_et_transylvania">Transylvania</placeName> we walked on foot from
					<placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/668090/comuna-sant.html">Újradna</placeName> till <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/724443/kosice.html">Kassa</placeName> without any <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832">food</term>. We got to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/724443/kosice.html">Kassa</placeName> the 20th of December. We were terribly crammed in the brick
					<term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-929">factory</term> of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/724443/kosice.html">Kassa</placeName>. It was cold, we had <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">no food</term> and suffered greatly. We were nearly
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">frozen</term>. The brick <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-929">factory</term> of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/724443/kosice.html">Kassa</placeName> had a very bad reputation. 7,000 people were kept there, out of
				whom many were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">frozen</term> and remained without
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">food</term>. In December, they <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">entrained</term> us, 75 of us in a freight car, not
				more. We got <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">food</term> once a day. One day we got
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">lunch</term>, the other day <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">dinner</term>, the next day <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">breakfast</term>. We got <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">no water</term> at all and could not buy it either
				because the freight car was locked. It was <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">full of
					lice</term> and people got <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">sick</term> one after
				the other. We had to use for the toilet either a great teapot or other pots. Signs of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-791" type="subject">spotted fever</term> could be noticed already on the
					<term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-940">train</term>. When we arrived there was a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">dead</term> person, the boy next to me. The journey
				lasted 9 days till <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/7872685/donnerskirchen.html">Donnerskirchen</placeName>. We arrived at 2 am
				after 9 days of travel and the <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_germans">Germans</term> ordered us to work already at
				6 am. We had to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">make trenches</term> and bunkers,
				and had no opportunity to wash. We had no <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject"
					>clothes</term> and some had to go to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject"
					>work</term> barefoot. Here a sergeant forced me to get out into the snow having a temperature of 40 degrees and he also <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">broke</term> my cheek-bone with a club. I stayed here
				9 days before I <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">escaped</term> with four of my
				friends in the possession of a service ticket which was forged. The 7th of January, we crossed the German-Hungarian border and arrived
				in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3045190/sopron.html">Sopron</placeName>. From <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3045190/sopron.html">Sopron</placeName> we went to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3052009/gyor.html">Győr</placeName>, where luckily we contracted <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-493" type="subject">typhus</term>, which meant 5 weeks stay in <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282" type="subject">hospital</term>, till the 1st of March. The winter was
				then over and we had a good life in the public <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282" type="subject"
					>hospital</term> of <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3052009/gyor.html">Győr</placeName>. Later, the 1st of March, a 1st
				lieutenant of the <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-474">Arrow Cross</orgName> ordered us to leave the
					<term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-282">hospital</term> and put us into the collecting
				place, the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-650" type="subject">prisoner</term>s’ <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp</term> of <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3052009/gyor.html">Győr</placeName>, from where we were taken to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2766162/schandorf.html">Schandorf</placeName>. The sergeant who received us seized all the few things
				we had, he took even razors and soaps, etc. The 20th of March, they took us to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/3044310/szombathely.html">Szombathely</placeName>, once again searched our luggage and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-655" type="subject">robbed</term> us anew, leaving only a blanket. <pb
					n="3" facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB1640_03.jpg"/> We then went to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2766162/schandorf.html"
					>Schandorf</placeName> on foot. Here we were crammed, 750 of us, in a single cellar. In <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/2766162/schandorf.html">Schandorf</placeName> we dug trenches and bunkers. We <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term> from 7 am till 4 pm. In the meantime we
				were maltreated, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-345" type="subject">beaten</term>, and struck. I left
				this <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp</term>, but later I heard it became an
				unbearable place where they <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">shot</term> people. Out
				of 750 people, 250 survived this <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp</term>. Out of
				my team of 40 people only 8 survived. The rest all <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject"
					>died</term> from <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-493" type="subject">typhus</term>. There were no
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-287" type="subject">doctors</term> at all. They kept these people in
				a special ward of a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-491" type="subject">hospital</term> but it
				practically meant a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">death</term> sentence. A <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-289">veterinarian</term> treated them but had no medicine,
				and people <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-570" type="subject">starvation</term>. <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">Food</term> was anyway extremely scarce. We set off
				from <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/2766162/schandorf.html">Schandorf</placeName> because of the <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004583">Russian</orgName> approach and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-517" type="subject">walked</term> for 16 days. We got food 6 times during
				these 16 days. The person who got tired or was out of step was <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532"
					type="subject">shot</term>. They treated us in an incredible way. An average of 40 people <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> per day. The 7th of April, in the forest
				at <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/7872422/eisenerz.html">Eisenerz</placeName>, which was one of the greatest metallurgical
				towns, the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">killed</term> 150 Jews with machine guns without any
				reason. About 10 centimetres behind my back my friend was <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532"
					type="subject">shot</term>, too, but we had to proceed, we could not stop. This is how we got to <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-570" type="camp">Mauthausen</placeName>. In <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-570" type="camp">Mauthausen</placeName> we lived in <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">tents</term>. After an <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1105" type="subject">air raid</term> at night 9 people remained <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">dead</term> and 20 were wounded. There was also
				another tragic event that affected my spirit a great deal. One of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1438" type="subject">supervisors</term> was beating a 50-year-old friend
				of mine badly when I jumped on him. He went to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject"
					>SS</term> to complain about me. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-345" type="subject">beat</term> me up so much that they broke my ribs
				and the bone of my little finger. <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">Food</term> was
				terribly poor. For breakfast we got 0.2 litre of bitter black <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831"
					type="subject">coffee</term>, at noon some turnip <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831"
					type="subject">soup</term>, and in the evening 100 grams of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831"
					type="subject">bread</term>. That was all for a day. It was only natural that we became feeble and many <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745">died</term>. <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745">Death</term> was caused by <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-493" type="subject">typhus</term>, by <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-570" type="subject">starvation</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-345" type="subject">beating</term>. From <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-570" type="camp">Mauthausen</placeName> we went to <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-584" type="camp">Gunskirchen</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-517" type="subject">walking</term> for four days. We were <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-570" type="subject">starving</term> a lot on the way; we ate grass,
				nettles, and leaves. If they noticed that someone was out of step they <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">shot</term> him, they <term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532">shot</term> also those weak people who could not carry on <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-517" type="subject">walking</term>, so there were a great number of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-515" type="subject">dead bodies</term> lying on the road. 50 men were sent
				ahead to dig <term type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-748">graves</term>. Once, an <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS</term> soldier disliked the work of a gravedigger.
				He made him stand in the grave and beat him till he <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject"
					>died</term>. One could see the inner parts of his skull, that is how much he beat him. It was a terrible view. The others then
				covered him with soil. <pb n="4" facs="EHRI-ET-DEGOB1640_04.jpg"/> When we arrived in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-584" type="camp">Gunskirchen</placeName> we were put up in wooden huts.
				They <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">crammed</term> 2,000 people in a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">barrack</term> for 500. We were terribly cramped,
				could not lie down, and slept sitting on the rucksacks. Later, I learnt from the <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004289">Americans</orgName> that they found arsenic in dissected <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-515">dead bodies</term>. They put little portions into the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term> that caused the general <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-494" type="subject">diarrhoea</term>. If someone went to the toilet he
				could not get there because he was <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">shot</term> by
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS</term>. We were very much <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">full of lice</term>; there was no water to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">wash</term>, not even for <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">drinking</term>. Sometimes we got a decilitre of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">water</term> and could decide to use it for drinking
				or for washing. <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">Food</term> was turnip <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">soup</term> all the time, and ca. 70 grams of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">bread</term>. Here they did not beat us, they just
				simply <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">shot</term> the people they disliked or
				against whom there were complaints. One day we were carrying the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745"
					type="subject">dead</term>. One of the boys ran out of energy and put the body down before it was allowed. He was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">shot</term>. Around 150-200 of us <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> daily, completely feeble people who either
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">died</term> of exhaustion or of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-493" type="subject">typhus</term>. We had to bury them in a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1321" type="subject">pit</term>. The <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004289">Americans</orgName> found this <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1321" type="subject">pit</term>; that was when they found out about
				arsenic poisoning. The <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004289">Americans</orgName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-573" type="subject">liberated</term> us the <date when="1945-05-04">4th
					of May, 1945</date>, and we started to do better. These were my own experiences.</p>
		</body>
